DOCUMENT();

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGstandard.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
#           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "MathObjects.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
          # "parserNumberWithUnits.pl",
          # "parserFormulaWithUnits.pl",
          # "parserFormulaUpToConstant.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
          );

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");

$x[1] = random(3,9,2);
$y[1] = $x[1] * 180;

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;


Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
An angle of \( $x[1] \pi \) radians can be converted to an angle of \{ ans_rule(5) \} degrees.
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS(Compute("$y[1]")->cmp() );

#ANS(num_cmp( $y[1] ) );


Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR

In order to change from radians to degrees, we multiply the number of
radians by \( \frac{180}{\pi} \), so we have
$PAR
\( $x[1] \pi \cdot \frac{180}{\pi} = $y[1]^{\circ} \)
$BR
END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;


COMMENT('MathObject version');
ENDDOCUMENT();
